# ONCE — Poems I & II
*by E.I. Werner*

---

## I. ONCE
*I/VII · 98 words*

Once,
Only one, only Darkness.
At once, Light declares Itself.
Severs one to two, before to after.

Light is holy.
Light is whole.
Light is epicene.
Light is Itself.

Darkness yearns, yearns to be one again.
Darkness swallows, swallows Light.
Within one singular seed.

Still, Light loves.
Loves to be and become.
One seed cannot contain It.

At once,
Light shines, shatters one seed.
A golden Sun emerges.

Still, Sun loves.
Loves to be and bestow Itself.
Sun severs of Itself, seven planets to behold It.
Severed, Sun is less than It was.
Beheld, Darkness cannot claim them.

---

## II. MOTHER
*II/VII · 96 words*

Sun severs seven children of Itself,
One, unlike her brothers.
She, the only daughter of Sun.
Sun beholds Itself glimmering,
In her sweet waters.

She dances, dances around Sun,
Until She dances where She began.
There, She beholds Sun without shadow,
So beholds her own.

Sun is all Light,
She, half-shadow.
Sun is epicenity Itself,
She, only Its daughter.

She twirls, twirls,
To escape Her shadow.
She weeps, weeps,
Shame will not release Her.

Two tears fall, fall,
To dawn, to dusk.
Salt cuts sweet,
Shame meets awe.

Son and son born.
So daughter become Mother.
